# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hexbin-maps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Choropleth maps provide an easy way to visualize how a variable varies across a geographic area or show the level of variability within a region.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] A heat map or isarithmic map is similar but uses regions drawn according to the pattern of the variable, rather than the *a priori* geographic areas of choropleth maps.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] The earliest known choropleth map was created in 1826 by Baron Pierre Charles Dupin, depicting the availability of basic education in France by department.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] More "*cartes teintées*" ("tinted maps") were soon produced in France to visualize other "moral statistics" on education, disease, crime, and living conditions.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Choropleth maps quickly gained popularity in several countries due to the increasing availability of demographic data compiled from national Censuses, starting with a series of choropleth maps published in the official reports of the 1841 Census of Ireland.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] When Chromolithography became widely available after 1850, color was increasingly added to choropleth maps.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] The term "choropleth map" was introduced in 1938 by the geographer John Kirtland Wright, and was in common usage among cartographers by the 1940s.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Also in 1938, Glenn Trewartha reintroduced them as "ratio maps", but this term did not survive.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] A choropleth map brings together two datasets: spatial data representing a partition of geographic space into distinct *districts*, and *statistical data* representing a variable aggregated within each district.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] There are two common conceptual models of how these interact in a choropleth map: in one view, which may be called "district dominant", the districts (often existing governmental units) are the focus, in which a variety of attributes are collected, including the variable being mapped.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] In the other view, which may be called "variable dominant", the focus is on the variable as a geographic phenomenon (say, the Latino population), with a real-world distribution, and the partitioning of it into districts is merely a convenient measurement technique.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] That is, boundaries of the colored districts may or may not coincide with the location of changes in the geographic distribution being studied.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] This is in direct contrast to chorochromatic and isarithmic maps, in which region boundaries are defined by patterns in the geographic distribution of the subject phenomenon.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] A prime example of this would be elections, in which the vote total for each district determines its elected representative.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] However, it can result in a number of issues, generally due to the fact that the constant color applied to each aggregation district makes it look homogeneous, masking an unknown degree of variation of the variable within the district.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] For example, a city may include neighborhoods of low, moderate, and high family income, but be colored with one constant "moderate" color.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Thus, real-world spatial patterns may not conform to the regional unit symbolized.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Because of this, issues such as the ecological fallacy and the modifiable areal unit problem (MAUP) can lead to major misinterpretations of the data depicted, and other techniques are preferable if one can obtain the necessary data.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] These issues can be somewhat mitigated by using smaller districts, because they show finer variations in the mapped variable, and their smaller visual size and increased number reduces the likelihood that the map user makes judgments about the variation within a single district.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] However, they can make the map overly complex, especially if there is not a meaningful geographic pattern in the variable (i.e., the map looks like randomly scattered colors).
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Although representing specific data in large regions can be misleading, the familiar district shapes can make the map clearer and easier to interpret and remember.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] The choice of regions will ultimately depend on the map's intended audience and purpose.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Alternatively, the dasymetric technique can sometimes be employed to refine the region boundaries to more closely match actual changes in the subject phenomenon.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Because of these issues, for many variables, one may prefer an isarithmic (for a quantitative variable) or chorochromatic map (for a qualitative variable), in which the region boundaries are based on the data itself.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] However, in many cases such detailed information is simply not available, and the choropleth map is the only feasible option.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] The variable can also be in any of Stevens' levels of measurement: nominal, ordinal, interval, or ratio, although quantitative (interval/ratio) variables are more commonly used in choropleth maps than qualitative (nominal/ordinal) variables.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] The level of measurement of the individual datum may be different than the aggregate summary statistic.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] For example, a census may ask each individual for his or her "primary spoken language" (nominal), but this may be summarized over all of the individuals in a county as "percent primarily speaking Spanish" (ratio) or as "predominant primary language" (nominal).
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Normalization is the technique of deriving a spatially intensive variable from one or more spatially extensive variables, so that it can be appropriately used in a choropleth map.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] It is similar, but not identical, to the technique of normalization or standardization in statistics.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Typically, it is accomplished by computing the ratio between two spatially extensive variables.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] These are not equivalent, nor is one better than another.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Rather, they tell different aspects of a geographic narrative.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] For example, a choropleth map of the population density of the Latino population in Texas visualizes a narrative about the spatial clustering and distribution of that group, while a map of the percent Latino visualizes a narrative of composition and predominance.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Failure to employ proper normalization will lead to an inappropriate and potentially misleading map in almost all cases.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] This is one of the most common mistakes in cartography, with one study finding that at one point, more than half of United States COVID-19 dashboards hosted by state governments were not employing normalization to their choropleth maps.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] This is one of many issues that contributed to the infodemic surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic, and "might also be a subtle facilitator of the extreme political polarization surrounding measures to combat COVID that has occurred in the United States".
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Every choropleth map has a strategy for mapping values to colors.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] A *classified* choropleth map separates the range of values into classes, with all of the districts in each class being assigned the same color.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] An *unclassed* map (sometimes called *n-class*) directly assigns a color proportional to the value of each district.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Starting with Dupin's 1826 map, classified choropleth maps have been far more common.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] It is likely that this was originally due to the greater simplicity of applying a limited set of tints; only in the age of computerized cartography have unclassed choropleth maps even been feasible, and until recently, they were still not easy to create in most mapping software.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Tobler, in formally introducing the unclassed scheme in 1973, asserted that it was a more accurate depiction of the original data, and stated that the primary argument in favor of classification, that it is more readable, needed to be tested.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Thus, they are able to better see the general patterns in the geographic phenomenon, but not the specific values.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] The primary argument in favor of classed choropleth maps is that it is easier for readers to process, due to the fewer number of distinct shades to recognize, which reduces cognitive load and allows them to precisely match the colors in the map to the values listed in the legend.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Classification is performed by establishing a *classification rule*, a series of thresholds that partitions the quantitative range of variable values into a series of ordered classes.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] For example, if a dataset of annual Median income by U.S. county includes values between US$20,000 and $150,000, it could be broken into three classes at thresholds of $45,000 and $83,000.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] To avoid confusion, any classification rule should be mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive, meaning that any possible value falls into exactly one class.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] For example, if a rule establishes a threshold at the value 6.5, it needs to be clear about whether a district with a value of exactly 6.5 will be classified into the lower or upper class (i.e., whether the definition of the lower class is <6.5 or ≤6.5 and whether the upper class is >6.5 or ≥6.5).
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Because calculated thresholds can often be at precise values that are not easily interpretable by map readers (e.g., $74,326.9734), it is common to create a *modified classification rule* by rounding threshold values to a similar simple number.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] The final element of a choropleth map is the set of colors used to represent the different values of the variable.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] A second general guideline, at least for classified maps, is that the colors should be easily distinguishable, so the colors on the map can be unambiguously matched to those in the legend to determine the represented values.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] This requirement limits the number of classes that can be included; for shades of gray, tests have shown that when value alone is used (e.g., light to dark, whether gray or any single hue), it is difficult to practically use more than seven classes.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] If differences in hue and/or saturation are incorporated, that limit increases significantly to as many as 10-12 classes.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] The need for color discrimination is further impacted by color vision deficiencies; for example, color schemes that use red and green to distinguish values will not be useful for a significant portion of the population.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] It is possible to represent two (and sometimes three) variables simultaneously on a single choropleth map by representing each with a single-hue progression and blending the colors of each district.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] This technique was first published by the U.S.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Census Bureau in the 1970s, and has been used many times since, to varying degrees of success.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] This technique is generally used to visualize the correlation and contrast between two variables hypothesized to be closely related, such as educational attainment and income.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Contrasting but not complementary colors are generally used, so that their combination is intuitively recognized as "between" the two original colors, such as red+blue=purple.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] The technique works best when the geography of the variable has a high degree of spatial autocorrelation, so that there are large regions of similar colors with gradual changes between them; otherwise the map can look like a confusing mix of random colors.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] They have been found to be more easily used if the map includes a carefully designed legend and an explanation of the technique.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] A choropleth map uses *ad hoc* symbols to represent the mapped variable.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] While the general strategy may be intuitive if a color progression is chosen that reflects the proper order, map readers cannot decipher the actual value of each district without a legend.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] A typical choropleth legend for a classed choropleth map includes a series of sample patches of the symbol for each class, with a text description of the corresponding range of values.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] On an unclassed choropleth map, it is common for the legend to show a smooth color gradient between the minimum and maximum values, with two or more points along it labeled with corresponding values.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] An alternative approach is the *histogram legend*, which includes a histogram showing the frequency distribution of the mapped variable (i.e., the number of districts in each class).
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Each class may be represented by a single bar with its width determined by its minimum and maximum threshold values and its height calculated such that the box area is proportional to the number of districts included, then colored with the map symbol used for that class.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] Alternatively, the histogram may be divided into a large number of bars, such that each class includes one or more bars, symbolized according to its symbol in the map.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] This form of legend shows not only the threshold values for each class, but gives some context for the source of those values, especially for endogenous classification rules that are based on the frequency distribution, such as quantiles.
[src:hexbin-maps/choropleth-map] However, they are not currently supported in GIS and mapping software, and must typically be constructed manually.
[src:hexbin-maps/data-binning] In digital image processing, "binning" has a very different meaning.
[src:hexbin-maps/data-binning] Pixel binning is the process of combining blocks of adjacent pixels throughout an image, by summing or averaging their values, during or after readout.
[src:hexbin-maps/data-binning] It reduces the amount of data; also the relative noise level in the result is lower.
[src:hexbin-maps/data-binning] Histograms are an example of data binning used in order to observe underlying frequency distributions.
[src:hexbin-maps/data-binning] They typically occur in one-dimensional space and in equal intervals for ease of visualization.
[src:hexbin-maps/data-binning] A straightforward way to cope with this problem is by using binning techniques in which the spectrum is reduced in resolution to a sufficient degree to ensure that a given peak remains in its bin despite small spectral shifts between analyses.
[src:hexbin-maps/data-binning] For example, in NMR the chemical shift axis may be discretized and coarsely binned, and in MS the spectral accuracies may be rounded to an integer multiple of the dalton.
[src:hexbin-maps/data-binning] Also, several digital camera systems incorporate an automatic pixel binning function to improve image contrast.
[src:hexbin-maps/data-binning] Binning is also used in machine learning to speed up the decision-tree boosting method for supervised classification and regression in algorithms such as Microsoft's LightGBM and scikit-learn's Histogram-based Gradient Boosting Classification Tree.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] A **heat map** (or **heatmap**) is a two-dimensional data visualization technique that represents the magnitude of individual values within a dataset as a color.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The variation in color may be by hue or intensity.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] In some applications such as crime analytics or website click-tracking, color is used to represent the *density* of data points rather than a value associated with each point.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] "Heat map" is a relatively new term, but the practice of shading matrices has existed for over a century.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Heat maps originated in 2D displays of the values in a data matrix.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Larger values were represented by small dark gray or black squares (pixels) and smaller values by lighter squares.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The earliest known example dates to 1873, when Toussaint Loua used a hand-drawn and colored shaded matrix to visualize social statistics across the districts of Paris.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The idea of reordering rows and columns to reveal structure in a data matrix, known as seriation, was introduced by Flinders Petrie in 1899.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] In 1950, Louis Guttman developed the Scalogram, a method for ordering binary matrices to expose a one-dimensional scale structure.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] In 1957, Peter Sneath displayed the results of a cluster analysis by permuting the rows and the columns of a matrix to place similar values near each other according to the clustering.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] This idea was implemented by Robert Ling in 1973 with a computer program called SHADE.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Ling used overstruck printer characters to represent different shades of gray, one character-width per pixel.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Leland Wilkinson developed the first computer program in 1994 (SYSTAT) to produce cluster heat maps with high-resolution color graphics.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The Eisen et al. display shown in the figure is a replication of the earlier SYSTAT design.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Software designer Cormac Kinney trademarked the term 'heat map' in 1991 to describe computer software used to display real-time financial market information.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] In 1998 the trademark was acquired by SS&C Technologies, Inc., but the company did not extend the license, so it was annulled in 2006.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] There are two primary categories of heat maps: spatial and grid.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Additionally, there are over ten various types of heat maps.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] A **spatial heat map** displays the magnitude of a spatial phenomenon as color, usually cast over a map.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] In the image labeled "Spatial Heat Map Example," temperature is displayed by color range across a map of the world.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Color ranges from blue (cold) to red (hot).
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] A **grid heat map** displays magnitude as color in a two-dimensional matrix, with each dimension representing a category of trait and the color representing the magnitude of some measurement on the combined traits from each of the two categories.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] For example, one dimension might represent year, and the other dimension might represent month, and the value measured might be temperature.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] This heat map would show how temperature changed over the years in each month.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Grid heat maps are further categorized into two different types of matrices: clustered, and correlogram.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] In a grid heat map, colors are presented in a grid of a fixed size, with every cell in the grid also being an equal size and shape.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The goal is to detect clustering, or suggest the presence of clusters.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] A spatial heat map is often used on maps or satellite imagery (see GIS), where there is no concept of cells, and instead the colors vary continuously.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Heat maps have a wide range of possibilities amongst applications due to their ability to simplify data and make for visually appealing to read data analysis.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Many applications using different types of heat maps are listed below.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Business Analysis: Heat maps are used in business analytics to give a visual representation about a company's current functioning, performance, and the need for improvements.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Heat maps are a way to analyze a company's existing data and update it to reflect growth and other specific efforts.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Heat maps visually appeal to team members and clients of the business or company.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Websites: There are many different ways heat maps are used within websites to determine a visiting users actions.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Typically, there are multiple heat maps used together to determine insight to a website on what are the best and worst performing elements on the page.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Some specific heat maps used for website analysis are listed below.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Exploratory Data Analysis: Working with small and large data sets, data scientists and data analysts look at and determine essential relationships and characteristics amongst different points in a data set as well as features of those data points.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Data scientists and analysts work with a team of others in different professions.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The use of heat maps make for a visually easy way to summarize findings and main components.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] There are other ways to represent data, however heat maps can visualize these data points and their relationships in a high dimensional space without becoming too compact and visually unappealing.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Heat maps in data analysis, allow for specific variables of rows and/or columns on the axes and even on the diagonal.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Biology: In the biological field, heat maps are used to visually represent large and small sets of data.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The focus is towards patterns and similarities in DNA, RNA, gene expression, etc.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Financial Analysis: The values of different product and assets fluctuate both rapidly and/or gradually over time.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The need to log changes to the daily markets is imperative.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] It allows for the ability to draw predictions from patterns while being able to revisit past numerical data.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Heat maps are able to remove the tedious process and enable the user to visualize data points and compare amongst the different performers.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Geographical Visualization: Heat maps are used to visualize and display a geographic distribution of data.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Heat maps represent different densities of data points on a geographical map to help users see the intensities of certain phenomena and to show items of most or least importance.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Heat maps used in geographical visualization are sometimes confused with choropleth maps, but the difference comes with how certain data is presented which differentiate the two.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Sports: Heat maps can be used in many sports and can influence manager's and/or coaches decisions based on high and low densities of data displayed.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Users can identify patterns within the game, the strategies of opponents and one's own team, make more informed decisions benefitting the player, team, and business, and can enhance performance in different areas by identifying enhancement is needed.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Heat maps also visualize comparisons and relationships amongst different teams in the same sport or between different sports all together.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Cybersecurity: In intrusion detection systems and log analysis, heat maps are used to highlight unusual access patterns, port scanning attempts, and malicious IP clustering.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] They help SOC (Security Operations Center) analysts quickly spot anomalies in large datasets.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Urban Planning: Heat maps are used in urban planning to visualize traffic congestion, pedestrian flow, and environmental conditions for data-driven infrastructure development (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Environmental heat maps track air quality and urban heat islands, guiding green space planning (EEA, 2021).
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Noise pollution heat maps aid zoning and mitigation near residential areas (EEA, 2020).
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Commercial planners use foot traffic heat maps to optimize retail layouts (SmartSantander, 2014).
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Integrated in smart city systems, these maps enhance livability, sustainability, and safety (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Many different color schemes can be used to illustrate the heat map, with perceptual advantages and disadvantages for each.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Choosing a good color scheme is integral to accurately and effectively displaying data, whereas a poor color scheme can lead viewers to inaccurate conclusions or exclude those with color deficiencies from proper analysis of said data.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Rainbow color maps, while a common choice, suffer from both accessibility and data continuity concerns.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Rainbow maps pose a challenge for users with color vision deficiencies, particularly in those with issues distinguishing red and green – a condition affecting a significant portion of the population.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] In addition to accessibility issues, rainbow heat map colors are not perceptually uniform; equal increments in data values do not correspond to equal changes in color.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The lack of uniformity can create misleading visual effects, like an artificial boundary or gradient.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] These effects can compromise the accuracy of effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] This example of the amplitude with the colors showcasing the phase angle can be hard to interpret with the entire rainbow of colors.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] In this case, the rainbow color scheme may cloud interpretation for those with color vision deficiencies or create confusion by some of the hard color boundaries across the diagram.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] To address these challenges, perceptually uniform color sets have been created to accommodate visual impairments and maintain consistent color differences proportional to differences in data.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Perceptually uniform color schemes are carefully designed to maintain consistent perceptual differences and offer a better viewing experience for viewers with color vision deficiencies.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] When implementing these color schemes into a heat map, designers must consider the data context and intended emphasis.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] These schemes follow three main patterns: sequential gradients (varying intensity of a single hue), diverging palettes (two contrasting hues with a neutral midpoint), and qualitative sets for categorical data.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Scientific visualization has produced several perceptually uniform color sets (like Viridis, Magma, and Cividis) that address both uniformity and accessibility concerns.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Device limitations can also significantly affect heat map visualization effectiveness.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] When displayed on low-resolution screens, highly detailed color gradients may appear pixelated or banded, reducing the quality of the visualization; this is known as color quantization, which can obscure or wrongly emphasize pieces of data.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] To mitigate these effects, designers should consider all devices that will display their heat map, and their color limitations.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Comprehensive testing and using a scheme with few colors is the safest bet when creating a heat map that will be viewed across multiple device types.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Grey-scale compatibility is essential for heat map accessibility, especially when considering print media, black and white only displays, or monochromatic vision.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] When converting to grey-scale, many color schemes will lose their distinctive data mappings, allowing for different values to appear identical in luminescence.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Grey-scale friendly color schemes are designed to incorporate contrast between data points even when color is removed, such as the "virdis" family.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Choropleth maps and heat maps are often used in place of one another incorrectly when referring to data visualized geographically.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Both techniques show the proportion of a variable of interest, but the two differ in how the boundaries for the variable's data aggregations are constructed.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] If the data were collected and aggregated using irregular boundaries, such as administrative units, then a heat map displaying that data will be the same as a choropleth map, encouraging confusion about how the two differ.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Choropleth maps show data grouped by geographic boundaries like countries, states, provinces or even floodplains.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Each region has a singular value, visualized by color intensity, shading or pattern.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a choropleth map showing the United States' population density by state may be used as an example.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The figure illustrates a singular value (population) denoted by blue color intensity proportionate to the state's value relative to all other states' values, bounded by each state's border.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Similarly, heat maps may also visualize data over a geographic region.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] However, unlike choropleth maps, heat maps show the proportion of a variable over an arbitrary, but usually small grid size, independent of geographic boundaries.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population is an example.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The figure illustrates a single value (population) bounded in an arbitrary grid (square kilometers) with each cell in the grid represented by a color intensity proportionate to the value of the cell relative to all other cells.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Some heat maps that are created using approximated regional data may show familiar geographic borders in the visualization where none really exist.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The illusion of geographic borders is due to the existence of patterns within the dataset rather than the visualization technique.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population also contains this occurrence.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Areas in rural parts of the United States and South America may closely resemble familiar geographic borders in those regions.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] Another example of a heatmap over a geographic area is a visualization of lake effect snow around Buffalo, New York, in mid-October 2006.
[src:hexbin-maps/heat-map] This figure shows another usage of heat maps with geographic areas, and how useful they can be in showcasing the effects of weather on specific areas as opposed to countries or states.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] In statistics, **kernel density estimation** (**KDE**) is the application of kernel smoothing for probability density estimation, i.e., a non-parametric method to estimate the probability density function of a random variable based on *kernels* as weights.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] KDE answers a fundamental data smoothing problem where inferences about the population are made based on a finite data sample.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] In some fields such as signal processing and econometrics it is also termed the **Parzen–Rosenblatt window** method, after Emanuel Parzen and Murray Rosenblatt, who are usually credited with independently creating it in its current form.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] One of the famous applications of kernel density estimation is in estimating the class-conditional marginal densities of data when using a naive Bayes classifier, which can improve its prediction accuracy.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Let $\mathbf {x} =\left(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},...\right)$ be independent and identically distributed samples drawn from some univariate distribution with an unknown density *f* at any given point x.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] We are interested in estimating the shape of this function *f*.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] A kernel with subscript h is called the *scaled kernel* and defined as *K**h*(*x*) = ⁠1/*h*⁠ *K*(⁠*x*/*h*⁠).
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Intuitively one wants to choose h as small as the data will allow; however, there is always a trade-off between the bias of the estimator and its variance.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The choice of bandwidth is discussed in more detail below.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] A range of kernel functions are commonly used: uniform, triangular, biweight, triweight, Epanechnikov (parabolic), normal, and others.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The Epanechnikov kernel is optimal in a mean square error sense, though the loss of efficiency is small for the kernels listed previously.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Due to its convenient mathematical properties, the normal kernel is often used, which means *K*(*x*) = *ϕ*(*x*), where ϕ is the standard normal density function.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The construction of a kernel density estimate finds interpretations in fields outside of density estimation.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] For example, in thermodynamics, this is equivalent to the amount of heat generated when heat kernels (the fundamental solution to the heat equation) are placed at each data point locations *xi*.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Similar methods are used to construct discrete Laplace operators on point clouds for manifold learning (e.g. diffusion map).
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Kernel density estimates are closely related to histograms, but can be endowed with properties such as smoothness or continuity by using a suitable kernel.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] For the histogram, first, the horizontal axis is divided into sub-intervals or bins which cover the range of the data: In this case, six bins each of width 2.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Whenever a data point falls inside this interval, a box of height 1/12 is placed there.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] If more than one data point falls inside the same bin, the boxes are stacked on top of each other.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] For the kernel density estimate, normal kernels with a standard deviation of 1.5 (indicated by the red dashed lines) are placed on each of the data points *xi*.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The kernels are summed to make the kernel density estimate (solid blue curve).
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The smoothness of the kernel density estimate (compared to the discreteness of the histogram) illustrates how kernel density estimates converge faster to the true underlying density for continuous random variables.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The bandwidth of the kernel is a free parameter which exhibits a strong influence on the resulting estimate.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] To illustrate its effect, we take a simulated random sample from the standard normal distribution (plotted at the blue spikes in the rug plot on the horizontal axis).
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The grey curve is the true density (a normal density with mean 0 and variance 1).
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] In comparison, the red curve is *undersmoothed* since it contains too many spurious data artifacts arising from using a bandwidth *h* = 0.05, which is too small.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The green curve is *oversmoothed* since using the bandwidth *h* = 2 obscures much of the underlying structure.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The black curve with a bandwidth of *h* = 0.337 is considered to be optimally smoothed since its density estimate is close to the true density.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] An extreme situation is encountered in the limit $h\to 0$ (no smoothing), where the estimate is a sum of n delta functions centered at the coordinates of analyzed samples.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] In the other extreme limit $h\to \infty$ the estimate retains the shape of the used kernel, centered on the mean of the samples (completely smooth).
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] where *o* is the little o notation, and n the sample size (as above).
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] where ${\textstyle R(g)=\int g(x)^{2}\,dx}$ for a function *g*, ${\textstyle m_{2}(K)=\int x^{2}K(x)\,dx}$ and $f''$ is the second derivative of f and K is the kernel.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Neither the AMISE nor the *h*AMISE formulas can be used directly since they involve the unknown density function f or its second derivative $f''$ .
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] To overcome that difficulty, a variety of automatic, data-based methods have been developed to select the bandwidth.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Several review studies have been undertaken to compare their efficacies, with the general consensus that the plug-in selectors and cross validation selectors are the most useful over a wide range of data sets.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Substituting any bandwidth h which has the same asymptotic order *n*−1/5 as *h*AMISE into the AMISE gives that AMISE(*h*) = *O*(*n*−4/5), where *O* is the big *O* notation.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] It can be shown that, under weak assumptions, there cannot exist a non-parametric estimator that converges at a faster rate than the kernel estimator.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Note that the *n*−4/5 rate is slower than the typical *n*−1 convergence rate of parametric methods.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] If the bandwidth is not held fixed, but is varied depending upon the location of either the estimate (balloon estimator) or the samples (pointwise estimator), this produces a particularly powerful method termed adaptive or variable bandwidth kernel density estimation.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Bandwidth selection for kernel density estimation of heavy-tailed distributions is relatively difficult.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] An h value is considered more robust when it improves the fit for long-tailed and skewed distributions or for bimodal mixture distributions.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Another modification that will improve the model is to reduce the factor from 1.06 to 0.9.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] This approximation is termed the *normal distribution approximation*, Gaussian approximation, or *Silverman's rule of thumb*.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] While this rule of thumb is easy to compute, it should be used with caution as it can yield widely inaccurate estimates when the density is not close to being normal.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The estimate based on the rule-of-thumb bandwidth is significantly oversmoothed.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] One difficulty with applying this inversion formula is that it leads to a diverging integral, since the estimate ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ is unreliable for large t's.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] To circumvent this problem, the estimator ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ is multiplied by a damping function *ψh*(*t*) = *ψ*(*ht*), which is equal to 1 at the origin and then falls to 0 at infinity.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The "bandwidth parameter" h controls how fast we try to dampen the function ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ .
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] In particular when h is small, then *ψh*(*t*) will be approximately one for a large range of t's, which means that ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ remains practically unaltered in the most important region of t's.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] The most common choice for function *ψ* is either the uniform function *ψ*(*t*) = **1**{−1 ≤ *t* ≤ 1}, which effectively means truncating the interval of integration in the inversion formula to [−1/*h*, 1/*h*], or the Gaussian function *ψ*(*t*) = *e**−πt*2.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] where *K* is the Fourier transform of the damping function *ψ*.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Thus the kernel density estimator coincides with the characteristic function density estimator.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Namely, M is the collection of points for which the density function is locally maximized.
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] A natural estimator of M is a plug-in from KDE, where $g(x)$ and $\lambda _{1}(x)$ are KDE version of $g(x)$ and $\lambda _{1}(x)$ .
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Under mild assumptions, $M_{c}$ is a consistent estimator of M .
[src:hexbin-maps/kernel-density-estimation] Note that one can use the mean shift algorithm to compute the estimator $M_{c}$ numerically.
[src:hexbin-maps/rawgraphs] The project was started in 2013 by a group of researchers of Politecnico di Milano with the original name of "RAW".
[src:hexbin-maps/rawgraphs] In the same year the tool won the "Most Beautiful" award at the Kantar Information is Beautiful Awards 2014 organized by David McCandless.
[src:hexbin-maps/rawgraphs] In 2017 the project was re-launched thanks to private support.
[src:hexbin-maps/rawgraphs] It changed the license from LGPL to Apache 2 and the project name to "RAWGraphs".
[src:hexbin-maps/rawgraphs] In August 2019 the team launched a crowdfunding campaign to harvest economical support for developing a new version of the tool.
[src:hexbin-maps/rawgraphs] Version 2.0.0 was released in September 2020 to backers, and publicly in February 2021.
[src:hexbin-maps/rawgraphs] The new version presents a modular architecture composed by a core JavaScript library, an expandable library of visual models, and a web-based GUI written in React.
[src:hexbin-maps/rawgraphs] RAWGraphs has been used in a number of research projects in academia, and is used also by journalist and graphic designer thanks to its ability of creating clean, SVG-based images that can be further edited with any other software.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] A **two-dimensional space** is a mathematical space with two dimensions, meaning points have two degrees of freedom: their locations can be locally described with two coordinates or they can move in two independent directions.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Common two-dimensional spaces are often called *planes* (especially the Euclidean plane), or, more generally, *surfaces*.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] These include analogs to physical spaces, like flat planes, and curved surfaces like spheres, cylinders, and cones, which can be infinite or finite.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Some two-dimensional mathematical spaces are not used to represent physical positions, like an affine plane or complex plane.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] The most basic example is the flat Euclidean plane, an idealization of a flat surface in physical space such as a sheet of paper or a chalkboard.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] On the Euclidean plane, any two points can be joined by a unique straight line along which the distance can be measured.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] The space is flat because any two lines transversed by a third line perpendicular to both of them are parallel, meaning they never intersect and stay at uniform distance from each-other.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Two-dimensional spaces can also be curved, for example the sphere and hyperbolic plane, sufficiently small portions of which appear like the flat plane, but on which straight lines which are locally parallel do not stay equidistant from each-other but eventually converge or diverge, respectively.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Two-dimensional spaces with a locally Euclidean concept of distance but which can have non-uniform curvature are called Riemannian surfaces.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Lorentzian surfaces look locally like a two-dimensional slice of relativistic spacetime with one spatial and one time dimension; constant-curvature examples are the flat Lorentzian plane (a two-dimensional subspace of Minkowski space) and the curved de Sitter and anti-de Sitter planes.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Other types of mathematical planes and surfaces modify or do away with the structures defining the Euclidean plane.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] For example, the affine plane has a notion of parallel lines but no notion of distance; however, signed areas can be meaningfully compared, as they can in a more general symplectic surface.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] The projective plane does away with both distance and parallelism.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] A two-dimensional metric space has some concept of distance but it need not match the Euclidean version.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] A topological surface can be stretched, twisted, or bent without changing its essential properties.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] An algebraic surface is a two-dimensional set of solutions of a system of polynomial equations.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Some mathematical spaces have additional arithmetical structure associated with their points.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] A vector plane is an affine plane whose points, called *vectors*, include a special designated origin or zero vector.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Vectors can be added together or scaled by a number, and optionally have a Euclidean, Lorentzian, or Galilean concept of distance.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] The complex plane, hyperbolic number plane, and dual number plane each have points which are considered numbers themselves, and can be added and multiplied.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] A Riemann surface or Lorentz surface appear locally like the complex plane or hyperbolic number plane, respectively.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Mathematical spaces are often defined or represented using numbers rather than geometric axioms.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] One of the most fundamental two-dimensional spaces is the real coordinate space, denoted $\mathbb {R} ^{2},$ consisting of pairs of real-number coordinates.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Sometimes the space represents arbitrary quantities rather than geometric positions, as in the parameter space of a mathematical model or the configuration space of a physical system.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] More generally, other types of numbers can be used as coordinates.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] The complex plane is two-dimensional when considered to be formed from real-number coordinates, but one-dimensional in terms of complex-number coordinates.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] A two-dimensional complex space – such as the two-dimensional complex coordinate space, the complex projective plane, or a complex surface – has two complex dimensions, which can alternately be represented using four real dimensions.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] A two-dimensional lattice is an infinite grid of points which can be represented using integer coordinates.
[src:hexbin-maps/two-dimensional-space] Some two-dimensional spaces, such as finite planes, have only a finite set of elements.
